<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><entry xml:lang="en" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:planet="http://planet.intertwingly.net/"><id>http://tcsmath.org/?p=2232</id><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/2015/11/21/follmers-drift-itos-lemma-and-the-log-sobolev-inequality/" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/><title>Follmer’s drift, Ito’s lemma, and the log-Sobolev inequality</title><summary type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">1. Construction of Föllmer’s drift In a previous post, we saw how an entropy-optimal drift process could be used to prove the Brascamp-Lieb inequalities. Our main tool was a result of Föllmer that we now recall and justify. Afterward, we will use it to prove the Gaussian log-Sobolev inequality. Consider with , where is the … <a class="more-link" href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/2015/11/21/follmers-drift-itos-lemma-and-the-log-sobolev-inequality/">Continue reading <span class="screen-reader-text">Follmer’s drift, Ito’s lemma, and the log-Sobolev inequality</span></a></div><div class="commentbar"><p/></div></summary><content type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p>
</p><p><b>1. Construction of Föllmer’s drift </b></p>
<p/><p>
In a <a href="http://tcsmath.org/2015/11/16/entropy-optimality-on-path-space/">previous post</a>, we saw how an entropy-optimal drift process could be used to prove the Brascamp-Lieb inequalities. Our main tool was a result of Föllmer that we now recall and justify. Afterward, we will use it to prove the Gaussian log-Sobolev inequality.</p>
<p>
Consider <img alt="{f : \mathbb R^n \rightarrow \mathbb R_+} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%3A+%5Cmathbb+R%5En+%5Crightarrow+%5Cmathbb+R_%2B%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f : \mathbb R^n \rightarrow \mathbb R_+} "/> with <img alt="{\int f \,d\gamma_n = 1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cint+f+%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n+%3D+1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\int f \,d\gamma_n = 1} "/>, where <img alt="{\gamma_n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma_n%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma_n} "/> is the standard Gaussian measure on <img alt="{\mathbb R^n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbb+R%5En%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathbb R^n} "/>. Let <img alt="{\{B_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BB_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{B_t\}} "/> denote an <img alt="{n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{n} "/>-dimensional Brownian motion with <img alt="{B_0=0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BB_0%3D0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{B_0=0} "/>. We consider all processes of the form <a name="eqdrift"/></p><a name="eqdrift">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  W_t = B_t + \int_0^t v_s\,ds\,, \ \ \ \ \ (1) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++W_t+%3D+B_t+%2B+%5Cint_0%5Et+v_s%5C%2Cds%5C%2C%2C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%281%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  W_t = B_t + \int_0^t v_s\,ds\,, \ \ \ \ \ (1) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqdrift"/> where <img alt="{\{v_s\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Bv_s%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{v_s\}} "/> is a progressively measurable drift and such that <img alt="{W_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_1} "/> has law <img alt="{f\,d\gamma_n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f\,d\gamma_n} "/>.</p>
<blockquote><p><b>Theorem 1 (Föllmer)</b> <em> <a name="thmfollmer"/> It holds that </em></p><em>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(f d\gamma_n \,\|\, d\gamma_n) = \min D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}) = \min \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2\,dt\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28f+d%5Cgamma_n+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+d%5Cgamma_n%29+%3D+%5Cmin+D%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%29+%3D+%5Cmin+%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cv_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(f d\gamma_n \,\|\, d\gamma_n) = \min D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}) = \min \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2\,dt\,,  "/></p>
</em><p><em> where the minima are over all processes of the form <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqdrift">(1)</a>. </em></p></blockquote>
<p/><p>
<em>Proof:</em>  In the <a href="http://tcsmath.org/2015/11/16/entropy-optimality-on-path-space/">preceding post</a> (Lemma 2), we have already seen that for any drift of the form <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqdrift">(1)</a>, it holds that </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(f d\gamma_n \,\|\,d\gamma_n) \leq \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2\,dt = D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]})\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28f+d%5Cgamma_n+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%29+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cv_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt+%3D+D%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%29%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(f d\gamma_n \,\|\,d\gamma_n) \leq \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2\,dt = D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]})\,,  "/></p>
<p> thus we need only exhibit a drift <img alt="{\{v_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Bv_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{v_t\}} "/> achieving equality.</p>
<p>
We define </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  v_t = \nabla \log P_{1-t} f(W_t) = \frac{\nabla P_{1-t} f(W_t)}{P_{1-t} f(W_t)}\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++v_t+%3D+%5Cnabla+%5Clog+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cnabla+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29%7D%7BP_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29%7D%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  v_t = \nabla \log P_{1-t} f(W_t) = \frac{\nabla P_{1-t} f(W_t)}{P_{1-t} f(W_t)}\,,  "/></p>
<p> where <img alt="{\{P_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BP_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{P_t\}} "/> is the Brownian semigroup defined by </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  P_t f(x) = \mathop{\mathbb E}[f(x + B_t)]\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++P_t+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Bf%28x+%2B+B_t%29%5D%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  P_t f(x) = \mathop{\mathbb E}[f(x + B_t)]\,.  "/></p>
<p> As we saw in the previous post (Lemma 2), the chain rule yields <a name="eqchain"/></p><a name="eqchain">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}) = \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2\,dt\,. \ \ \ \ \ (2) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%29+%3D+%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cv_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt%5C%2C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%282%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}) = \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2\,dt\,. \ \ \ \ \ (2) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqchain"/>  We are left to show that <img alt="{W_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_1} "/> has law <img alt="{f \,d\gamma_n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f \,d\gamma_n} "/> and <img alt="{D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}) = D(f d\gamma_n \,\|\,d\gamma_n)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%29+%3D+D%28f+d%5Cgamma_n+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}) = D(f d\gamma_n \,\|\,d\gamma_n)} "/>.</p>
<p>
We will prove the first fact using <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girsanov_theorem">Girsanov’s theorem</a> to argue about the change of measure between <img alt="{\{W_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_t\}} "/> and <img alt="{\{B_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BB_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{B_t\}} "/>. As in the previous post, we will argue somewhat informally using the heuristic that the law of <img alt="{dB_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BdB_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dB_t} "/> is a Gaussian random variable in <img alt="{\mathbb R^n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbb+R%5En%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathbb R^n} "/> with covariance <img alt="{dt \cdot I} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bdt+%5Ccdot+I%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dt \cdot I} "/>. Itô’s formula states that this heuristic is justified (see our use of the formula below).</p>
<p>
The following lemma says that, given any sample path <img alt="{\{W_s : s \in [0,t]\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_s+%3A+s+%5Cin+%5B0%2Ct%5D%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_s : s \in [0,t]\}} "/> of our process up to time <img alt="{s} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{s} "/>, the probability that Brownian motion (without drift) would have “done the same thing” is <img alt="{\frac{1}{M_t}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BM_t%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\frac{1}{M_t}} "/>.</p>
<blockquote><p><b>Remark 1</b> <em> I chose to present various steps in the next proof at varying levels of formality. The arguments have the same structure as corresponding formal proofs, but I thought (perhaps naïvely) that this would be instructive. </em></p></blockquote>
<p>
</p><blockquote><p><b>Lemma 2</b> <em><a name="lemgirsanov"/> Let <img alt="{\mu_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu_t} "/> denote the law of <img alt="{\{W_s : s \in [0,t]\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_s+%3A+s+%5Cin+%5B0%2Ct%5D%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_s : s \in [0,t]\}} "/>. If we define </em></p><em>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  M_t = \exp\left(-\int_0^t \langle v_s,dB_s\rangle - \frac12 \int_0^t \|v_s\|^2\,ds\right)\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++M_t+%3D+%5Cexp%5Cleft%28-%5Cint_0%5Et+%5Clangle+v_s%2CdB_s%5Crangle+-+%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5Et+%5C%7Cv_s%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cds%5Cright%29%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  M_t = \exp\left(-\int_0^t \langle v_s,dB_s\rangle - \frac12 \int_0^t \|v_s\|^2\,ds\right)\,,  "/></p>
<p> then under the measure <img alt="{\nu_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cnu_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\nu_t} "/> given by </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  d\nu_t = M_t \,d\mu_t\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++d%5Cnu_t+%3D+M_t+%5C%2Cd%5Cmu_t%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  d\nu_t = M_t \,d\mu_t\,,  "/></p>
</em><p><em> the process <img alt="{\{W_s : s \in [0,t]\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_s+%3A+s+%5Cin+%5B0%2Ct%5D%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_s : s \in [0,t]\}} "/> has the same law as <img alt="{\{B_s : s \in [0,t]\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BB_s+%3A+s+%5Cin+%5B0%2Ct%5D%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{B_s : s \in [0,t]\}} "/>. </em></p></blockquote>
<p/><p>
<em>Proof:</em>  We argue by analogy with the discrete proof. First, let us define the infinitesimal “transition kernel” of Brownian motion using our heuristic that <img alt="{dB_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BdB_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dB_t} "/> has covariance <img alt="{dt \cdot I} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bdt+%5Ccdot+I%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dt \cdot I} "/>: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  p(x,y) = \frac{e^{-\|x-y\|^2/2dt}}{(2\pi dt)^{n/2}}\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++p%28x%2Cy%29+%3D+%5Cfrac%7Be%5E%7B-%5C%7Cx-y%5C%7C%5E2%2F2dt%7D%7D%7B%282%5Cpi+dt%29%5E%7Bn%2F2%7D%7D%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  p(x,y) = \frac{e^{-\|x-y\|^2/2dt}}{(2\pi dt)^{n/2}}\,.  "/></p>
<p> We can also compute the (time-inhomogeneous) transition kernel <img alt="{q_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bq_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{q_t} "/> of <img alt="{\{W_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_t\}} "/>: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  q_t(x,y) = \frac{e^{-\|v_t dt + x - y\|^2/2dt}}{(2\pi dt)^{n/2}} = p(x,y) e^{-\frac12 \|v_t\|^2 dt} e^{-\langle v_t, x-y\rangle}\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++q_t%28x%2Cy%29+%3D+%5Cfrac%7Be%5E%7B-%5C%7Cv_t+dt+%2B+x+-+y%5C%7C%5E2%2F2dt%7D%7D%7B%282%5Cpi+dt%29%5E%7Bn%2F2%7D%7D+%3D+p%28x%2Cy%29+e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac12+%5C%7Cv_t%5C%7C%5E2+dt%7D+e%5E%7B-%5Clangle+v_t%2C+x-y%5Crangle%7D%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  q_t(x,y) = \frac{e^{-\|v_t dt + x - y\|^2/2dt}}{(2\pi dt)^{n/2}} = p(x,y) e^{-\frac12 \|v_t\|^2 dt} e^{-\langle v_t, x-y\rangle}\,.  "/></p>
<p> Here we are using that <img alt="{dW_t = dB_t + v_t\,dt} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BdW_t+%3D+dB_t+%2B+v_t%5C%2Cdt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dW_t = dB_t + v_t\,dt} "/> and <img alt="{v_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bv_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{v_t} "/> is deterministic conditioned on the past, thus the law of <img alt="{dW_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BdW_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dW_t} "/> is a normal with mean <img alt="{v_t\,dt} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bv_t%5C%2Cdt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{v_t\,dt} "/> and covariance <img alt="{dt \cdot I} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bdt+%5Ccdot+I%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dt \cdot I} "/>.</p>
<p>
To avoid confusion of derivatives, let’s use <img alt="{\alpha_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\alpha_t} "/> for the density of <img alt="{\mu_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmu_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mu_t} "/> and <img alt="{\beta_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\beta_t} "/> for the density of Brownian motion (recall that these are densities on paths). Now let us relate the density <img alt="{\alpha_{t+dt}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\alpha_{t+dt}} "/> to the density <img alt="{\alpha_{t}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha_%7Bt%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\alpha_{t}} "/>. We use here the notations <img alt="{\{\hat W_t, \hat v_t, \hat B_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B%5Chat+W_t%2C+%5Chat+v_t%2C+%5Chat+B_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{\hat W_t, \hat v_t, \hat B_t\}} "/> to denote a (non-random) sample path of <img alt="{\{W_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_t\}} "/>: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \begin{array}{lll}  \alpha_{t+dt}(\hat W_{[0,t+dt]}) &amp;= \alpha_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) q_t(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) \\ &amp;= \alpha_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) p(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) e^{-\frac12 \|\hat v_t\|^2\,dt-\langle \hat v_t,\hat W_t-\hat W_{t+dt}\rangle} \\ &amp;= \alpha_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) p(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) e^{-\frac12 \|\hat v_t\|^2\,dt+\langle \hat v_t,d \hat W_t\rangle} \\ &amp;= \alpha_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) p(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) e^{\frac12 \|\hat v_t\|^2\,dt+\langle \hat v_t, d \hat B_t\rangle}\,, \end{array}  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Blll%7D++%5Calpha_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%2Bdt%5D%7D%29+%26%3D+%5Calpha_t%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%5D%7D%29+q_t%28%5Chat+W_t%2C+%5Chat+W_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%29+%5C%5C+%26%3D+%5Calpha_t%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%5D%7D%29+p%28%5Chat+W_t%2C+%5Chat+W_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%29+e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac12+%5C%7C%5Chat+v_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt-%5Clangle+%5Chat+v_t%2C%5Chat+W_t-%5Chat+W_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%5Crangle%7D+%5C%5C+%26%3D+%5Calpha_t%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%5D%7D%29+p%28%5Chat+W_t%2C+%5Chat+W_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%29+e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac12+%5C%7C%5Chat+v_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt%2B%5Clangle+%5Chat+v_t%2Cd+%5Chat+W_t%5Crangle%7D+%5C%5C+%26%3D+%5Calpha_t%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%5D%7D%29+p%28%5Chat+W_t%2C+%5Chat+W_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%29+e%5E%7B%5Cfrac12+%5C%7C%5Chat+v_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt%2B%5Clangle+%5Chat+v_t%2C+d+%5Chat+B_t%5Crangle%7D%5C%2C%2C+%5Cend%7Barray%7D++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \begin{array}{lll}  \alpha_{t+dt}(\hat W_{[0,t+dt]}) &amp;= \alpha_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) q_t(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) \\ &amp;= \alpha_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) p(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) e^{-\frac12 \|\hat v_t\|^2\,dt-\langle \hat v_t,\hat W_t-\hat W_{t+dt}\rangle} \\ &amp;= \alpha_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) p(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) e^{-\frac12 \|\hat v_t\|^2\,dt+\langle \hat v_t,d \hat W_t\rangle} \\ &amp;= \alpha_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) p(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) e^{\frac12 \|\hat v_t\|^2\,dt+\langle \hat v_t, d \hat B_t\rangle}\,, \end{array}  "/></p>
<p> where the last line uses <img alt="{d\hat W_t = d\hat B_t + \hat v_t\,dt} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%5Chat+W_t+%3D+d%5Chat+B_t+%2B+%5Chat+v_t%5C%2Cdt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d\hat W_t = d\hat B_t + \hat v_t\,dt} "/>.</p>
<p>
Now by “heuristic” induction, we can assume <img alt="{\alpha_t(\hat W_{[0,t]})=\frac{1}{M_t} \beta_t(\hat W_{[0,t]})} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha_t%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%5D%7D%29%3D%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BM_t%7D+%5Cbeta_t%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%5D%7D%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\alpha_t(\hat W_{[0,t]})=\frac{1}{M_t} \beta_t(\hat W_{[0,t]})} "/>, yielding </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \begin{array}{lll}  \alpha_{t+dt}(\hat W_{[0,t+dt]}) &amp;= \frac{1}{M_t} \beta_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) p(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) e^{\frac12 \|\hat v_t\|^2\,dt+\langle \hat v_t, d \hat B_t\rangle} \\ &amp;= \frac{1}{M_{t+dt}} \beta_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) p(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) \\ &amp;= \frac{1}{M_{t+dt}} \beta_{t+dt}(\hat W_{[0,t+dt]})\,. \end{array}  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Blll%7D++%5Calpha_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%2Bdt%5D%7D%29+%26%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BM_t%7D+%5Cbeta_t%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%5D%7D%29+p%28%5Chat+W_t%2C+%5Chat+W_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%29+e%5E%7B%5Cfrac12+%5C%7C%5Chat+v_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt%2B%5Clangle+%5Chat+v_t%2C+d+%5Chat+B_t%5Crangle%7D+%5C%5C+%26%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BM_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%7D+%5Cbeta_t%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%5D%7D%29+p%28%5Chat+W_t%2C+%5Chat+W_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%29+%5C%5C+%26%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BM_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%7D+%5Cbeta_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%28%5Chat+W_%7B%5B0%2Ct%2Bdt%5D%7D%29%5C%2C.+%5Cend%7Barray%7D++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \begin{array}{lll}  \alpha_{t+dt}(\hat W_{[0,t+dt]}) &amp;= \frac{1}{M_t} \beta_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) p(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) e^{\frac12 \|\hat v_t\|^2\,dt+\langle \hat v_t, d \hat B_t\rangle} \\ &amp;= \frac{1}{M_{t+dt}} \beta_t(\hat W_{[0,t]}) p(\hat W_t, \hat W_{t+dt}) \\ &amp;= \frac{1}{M_{t+dt}} \beta_{t+dt}(\hat W_{[0,t+dt]})\,. \end{array}  "/></p>
<p> In the last line, we used the fact that <img alt="{p} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{p} "/> is the infinitesimal transition kernel for Brownian motion. <img alt="\Box" class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=eeeeee&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\Box"/></p>
<p>
Now we will show that <a name="eqtoestab"/></p><a name="eqtoestab">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  P_{1-t} f(W_t) = \exp\left(\frac12 \int_0^t \|v_s\|^2\,ds + \int_0^t \langle v_s, dB_s\rangle\right) = \frac{1}{M_t}\,. \ \ \ \ \ (3) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29+%3D+%5Cexp%5Cleft%28%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5Et+%5C%7Cv_s%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cds+%2B+%5Cint_0%5Et+%5Clangle+v_s%2C+dB_s%5Crangle%5Cright%29+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BM_t%7D%5C%2C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%283%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  P_{1-t} f(W_t) = \exp\left(\frac12 \int_0^t \|v_s\|^2\,ds + \int_0^t \langle v_s, dB_s\rangle\right) = \frac{1}{M_t}\,. \ \ \ \ \ (3) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqtoestab"/> From Lemma <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#lemgirsanov">2</a>, it will follow that <img alt="{W_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_t} "/> has the law <img alt="{(P_{1-t} f)\cdot d\nu_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%28P_%7B1-t%7D+f%29%5Ccdot+d%5Cnu_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{(P_{1-t} f)\cdot d\nu_t} "/> where <img alt="{d\nu_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%5Cnu_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d\nu_t} "/> is the law of <img alt="{B_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BB_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{B_t} "/>. In particular, <img alt="{W_1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_1} "/> has the law <img alt="{f\,d\nu_1 = f\,d\gamma_n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%5C%2Cd%5Cnu_1+%3D+f%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f\,d\nu_1 = f\,d\gamma_n} "/> which was our first goal.</p>
<p>
Given our preceding less formal arguments, let us use a proper stochastic calculus argument to establish <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqtoestab">(3)</a>. To do that we need a way to calculate <a name="eqderiv"/></p><a name="eqderiv">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  d \log P_{1-t} f(W_t) \quad \textrm{``}= \log P_{1-t-dt} f(W_{t+dt}) - \log P_{1-t} f(W_t)\textrm{''} \ \ \ \ \ (4) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++d+%5Clog+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29+%5Cquad+%5Ctextrm%7B%60%60%7D%3D+%5Clog+P_%7B1-t-dt%7D+f%28W_%7Bt%2Bdt%7D%29+-+%5Clog+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29%5Ctextrm%7B%27%27%7D+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%284%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  d \log P_{1-t} f(W_t) \quad \textrm{``}= \log P_{1-t-dt} f(W_{t+dt}) - \log P_{1-t} f(W_t)\textrm{''} \ \ \ \ \ (4) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqderiv"/> Notice that this involves both time and space derivatives.</p>
<p>
<b>Itô’s lemma.</b> Suppose we have a continuously differentiable function <img alt="{F : \mathbb R \times [0,1] \rightarrow \mathbb R} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF+%3A+%5Cmathbb+R+%5Ctimes+%5B0%2C1%5D+%5Crightarrow+%5Cmathbb+R%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{F : \mathbb R \times [0,1] \rightarrow \mathbb R} "/> that we write as <img alt="{F(x,t)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF%28x%2Ct%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{F(x,t)} "/> where <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/> is a space variable and <img alt="{t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{t} "/> is a time variable. We can expand <img alt="{d F} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd+F%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d F} "/> via its Taylor series: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  d F = \partial_t F \,dt + \partial_x F\,dx + \frac12 \partial_x^2 F\,dx^2 + \frac12 \partial_x \partial_t F\,dx\,dt + \cdots\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++d+F+%3D+%5Cpartial_t+F+%5C%2Cdt+%2B+%5Cpartial_x+F%5C%2Cdx+%2B+%5Cfrac12+%5Cpartial_x%5E2+F%5C%2Cdx%5E2+%2B+%5Cfrac12+%5Cpartial_x+%5Cpartial_t+F%5C%2Cdx%5C%2Cdt+%2B+%5Ccdots%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  d F = \partial_t F \,dt + \partial_x F\,dx + \frac12 \partial_x^2 F\,dx^2 + \frac12 \partial_x \partial_t F\,dx\,dt + \cdots\,.  "/></p>
<p> Normally we could eliminate the terms <img alt="{dx^2, dx\, dt} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bdx%5E2%2C+dx%5C%2C+dt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dx^2, dx\, dt} "/>, etc. since they are lower order as <img alt="{dx,dt \rightarrow 0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bdx%2Cdt+%5Crightarrow+0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dx,dt \rightarrow 0} "/>. But recall that for Brownian motion we have the heuristic <img alt="{\mathop{\mathbb E}[dB_t^2]=dt} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5BdB_t%5E2%5D%3Ddt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathop{\mathbb E}[dB_t^2]=dt} "/>. Thus we cannot eliminate the second-order space derivative if we plan to plug in <img alt="{x=B_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%3DB_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x=B_t} "/> (or <img alt="{x=W_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%3DW_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x=W_t} "/>, a process driven by Brownian motion). <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/It%C3%B4%27s_lemma">Itô’s lemma</a> says that this consideration alone gives us the correct result: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  d F(W_t,t) = \partial_t F(W_t,t)\,dt + \partial_x F(W_t,t)\,dW_t + \frac12 \partial_x^2 F(W_t,t)\,dt\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++d+F%28W_t%2Ct%29+%3D+%5Cpartial_t+F%28W_t%2Ct%29%5C%2Cdt+%2B+%5Cpartial_x+F%28W_t%2Ct%29%5C%2CdW_t+%2B+%5Cfrac12+%5Cpartial_x%5E2+F%28W_t%2Ct%29%5C%2Cdt%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  d F(W_t,t) = \partial_t F(W_t,t)\,dt + \partial_x F(W_t,t)\,dW_t + \frac12 \partial_x^2 F(W_t,t)\,dt\,.  "/></p>
<p> This generalizes in a straightforward way to the higher dimensional setting <img alt="{F : \mathbb R^n \times [0,1] \rightarrow \mathbb R} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF+%3A+%5Cmathbb+R%5En+%5Ctimes+%5B0%2C1%5D+%5Crightarrow+%5Cmathbb+R%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{F : \mathbb R^n \times [0,1] \rightarrow \mathbb R} "/>.</p>
<p>
With Itô’s lemma in hand, let us continue to calculate the derivative </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \begin{array}{lll}  d P_{1-t} f(W_t) &amp;= - \Delta P_{1-t} f(W_t)\,dt + \langle \nabla P_{1-t} f(W_t), dW_t\rangle + \Delta P_{1-t} f(W_t) \,dt \\ &amp;= \langle \nabla P_{1-t} f(W_t), dW_t\rangle \\ &amp;= P_{1-t} f(W_t) \,\langle v_t, dW_t\rangle\,. \end{array}  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cbegin%7Barray%7D%7Blll%7D++d+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29+%26%3D+-+%5CDelta+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29%5C%2Cdt+%2B+%5Clangle+%5Cnabla+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29%2C+dW_t%5Crangle+%2B+%5CDelta+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29+%5C%2Cdt+%5C%5C+%26%3D+%5Clangle+%5Cnabla+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29%2C+dW_t%5Crangle+%5C%5C+%26%3D+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29+%5C%2C%5Clangle+v_t%2C+dW_t%5Crangle%5C%2C.+%5Cend%7Barray%7D++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \begin{array}{lll}  d P_{1-t} f(W_t) &amp;= - \Delta P_{1-t} f(W_t)\,dt + \langle \nabla P_{1-t} f(W_t), dW_t\rangle + \Delta P_{1-t} f(W_t) \,dt \\ &amp;= \langle \nabla P_{1-t} f(W_t), dW_t\rangle \\ &amp;= P_{1-t} f(W_t) \,\langle v_t, dW_t\rangle\,. \end{array}  "/></p>
<p> For the time derivative (the first term), we have employed the heat equation </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \partial_t P_{1-t} f = - \Delta P_{1-t} f\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cpartial_t+P_%7B1-t%7D+f+%3D+-+%5CDelta+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \partial_t P_{1-t} f = - \Delta P_{1-t} f\,,  "/></p>
<p> where <img alt="{\Delta = \frac12 \sum_{i=1}^n \partial_{x_i}^2} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5CDelta+%3D+%5Cfrac12+%5Csum_%7Bi%3D1%7D%5En+%5Cpartial_%7Bx_i%7D%5E2%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\Delta = \frac12 \sum_{i=1}^n \partial_{x_i}^2} "/> is the Laplacian on <img alt="{\mathbb R^n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbb+R%5En%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathbb R^n} "/>.</p>
<p>
Note that the heat equation was already contained in our “infinitesimal density” <img alt="{p} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{p} "/> in the proof of Lemma <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#lemgirsanov">2</a>, or in the representation <img alt="{P_t = e^{t \Delta}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BP_t+%3D+e%5E%7Bt+%5CDelta%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{P_t = e^{t \Delta}} "/>, and Itô’s lemma was also contained in our heuristic that <img alt="{dB_t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BdB_t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dB_t} "/> has covariance <img alt="{dt \cdot I} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bdt+%5Ccdot+I%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dt \cdot I} "/>.</p>
<p>
Using Itô’s formula again yields </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  d \log P_{1-t} f(W_t) = \langle v_t, dW_t\rangle - \frac12 \|v_t\|^2\,dt = \frac12 \|v_t\|^2\,dt + \langle v_t,dB_t\rangle\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++d+%5Clog+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29+%3D+%5Clangle+v_t%2C+dW_t%5Crangle+-+%5Cfrac12+%5C%7Cv_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt+%3D+%5Cfrac12+%5C%7Cv_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt+%2B+%5Clangle+v_t%2CdB_t%5Crangle%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  d \log P_{1-t} f(W_t) = \langle v_t, dW_t\rangle - \frac12 \|v_t\|^2\,dt = \frac12 \|v_t\|^2\,dt + \langle v_t,dB_t\rangle\,.  "/></p>
<p> giving our desired conclusion <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqtoestab">(3)</a>.</p>
<p>
Our final task is to establish optimality: <img alt="{D\left(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}\right) = D(W_1\,\|\,B_1)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BD%5Cleft%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%5Cright%29+%3D+D%28W_1%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2CB_1%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{D\left(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}\right) = D(W_1\,\|\,B_1)} "/>. We apply the formula <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqtoestab">(3)</a>: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(W_1\,\|\,B_1) = \mathop{\mathbb E}[\log f(W_1)] = \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\frac12 \int_0^1 \|v_t\|^2\,dt\right],  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28W_1%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2CB_1%29+%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5B%5Clog+f%28W_1%29%5D+%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Cleft%5B%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5C%7Cv_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt%5Cright%5D%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(W_1\,\|\,B_1) = \mathop{\mathbb E}[\log f(W_1)] = \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\frac12 \int_0^1 \|v_t\|^2\,dt\right],  "/></p>
<p> where we used <img alt="{\mathop{\mathbb E}[\langle v_t,dB_t\rangle]=0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5B%5Clangle+v_t%2CdB_t%5Crangle%5D%3D0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathop{\mathbb E}[\langle v_t,dB_t\rangle]=0} "/>. Combined with <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqchain">(2)</a>, this completes the proof of the theorem. <img alt="\Box" class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&amp;bg=eeeeee&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\Box"/></p>
<p>
</p><p><b>2. The Gaussian log-Sobolev inequality </b></p>
<p/><p>
Consider again a measurable <img alt="{f : \mathbb R^n \rightarrow \mathbb R_+} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%3A+%5Cmathbb+R%5En+%5Crightarrow+%5Cmathbb+R_%2B%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f : \mathbb R^n \rightarrow \mathbb R_+} "/> with <img alt="{\int f\,d\gamma_n=1} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cint+f%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%3D1%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\int f\,d\gamma_n=1} "/>. Let us define <img alt="{\mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(f) = D(f\,d\gamma_n \,\|\,d\gamma_n)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathrm%7BEnt%7D_%7B%5Cgamma_n%7D%28f%29+%3D+D%28f%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(f) = D(f\,d\gamma_n \,\|\,d\gamma_n)} "/>. Then the classical log-Sobolev inequality in Gaussian space asserts that <a name="eqlogsob"/></p><a name="eqlogsob">
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(f) \leq \frac12 \int \frac{\|\nabla f\|^2}{f}\,d\gamma_n\,. \ \ \ \ \ (5) " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathrm%7BEnt%7D_%7B%5Cgamma_n%7D%28f%29+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac12+%5Cint+%5Cfrac%7B%5C%7C%5Cnabla+f%5C%7C%5E2%7D%7Bf%7D%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%5C%2C.+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%5C+%285%29+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(f) \leq \frac12 \int \frac{\|\nabla f\|^2}{f}\,d\gamma_n\,. \ \ \ \ \ (5) "/></p>
</a><p><a name="eqlogsob"/></p>
<p>
First, we discuss the correct way to interpret this. Define the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck semi-group <img alt="{\{U_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BU_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{U_t\}} "/> by its action </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  U_t f(x) = \mathop{\mathbb E}[f(e^{-t} x + \sqrt{1-e^{-2t}} B_1)]\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++U_t+f%28x%29+%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Bf%28e%5E%7B-t%7D+x+%2B+%5Csqrt%7B1-e%5E%7B-2t%7D%7D+B_1%29%5D%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  U_t f(x) = \mathop{\mathbb E}[f(e^{-t} x + \sqrt{1-e^{-2t}} B_1)]\,.  "/></p>
<p> This is the natural stationary diffusion process on Gaussian space. For every measurable <img alt="{f} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f} "/>, we have </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  U_t f \rightarrow \int f d\gamma_n \quad \textrm{ as } t \to \infty  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++U_t+f+%5Crightarrow+%5Cint+f+d%5Cgamma_n+%5Cquad+%5Ctextrm%7B+as+%7D+t+%5Cto+%5Cinfty++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  U_t f \rightarrow \int f d\gamma_n \quad \textrm{ as } t \to \infty  "/></p>
<p> or equivalently </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(U_t f) \rightarrow 0 \quad \textrm{ as } t \to \infty  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathrm%7BEnt%7D_%7B%5Cgamma_n%7D%28U_t+f%29+%5Crightarrow+0+%5Cquad+%5Ctextrm%7B+as+%7D+t+%5Cto+%5Cinfty++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(U_t f) \rightarrow 0 \quad \textrm{ as } t \to \infty  "/></p>
<p>
The log-Sobolev inequality yields quantitative convergence in the relative entropy distance as follows: Define the <em>Fisher information</em> </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  I(f) = \int \frac{\|\nabla f\|^2}{f} \,d\gamma_n\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++I%28f%29+%3D+%5Cint+%5Cfrac%7B%5C%7C%5Cnabla+f%5C%7C%5E2%7D%7Bf%7D+%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  I(f) = \int \frac{\|\nabla f\|^2}{f} \,d\gamma_n\,.  "/></p>
<p> One can check that </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \frac{d}{dt} \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n} (U_t f)\Big|_{t=0} = - I(f)\,,  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cfrac%7Bd%7D%7Bdt%7D+%5Cmathrm%7BEnt%7D_%7B%5Cgamma_n%7D+%28U_t+f%29%5CBig%7C_%7Bt%3D0%7D+%3D+-+I%28f%29%5C%2C%2C++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \frac{d}{dt} \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n} (U_t f)\Big|_{t=0} = - I(f)\,,  "/></p>
<p> thus the Fisher information describes the instantaneous decay of the relative entropy of <img alt="{f} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f} "/> under diffusion.</p>
<p>
So we can rewrite the log-Sobolev inequality as: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  - \frac{d}{dt} \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(U_t f)\Big|_{t=0} \geq 2 \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(f)\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++-+%5Cfrac%7Bd%7D%7Bdt%7D+%5Cmathrm%7BEnt%7D_%7B%5Cgamma_n%7D%28U_t+f%29%5CBig%7C_%7Bt%3D0%7D+%5Cgeq+2+%5Cmathrm%7BEnt%7D_%7B%5Cgamma_n%7D%28f%29%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  - \frac{d}{dt} \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(U_t f)\Big|_{t=0} \geq 2 \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(f)\,.  "/></p>
<p> This expresses the intuitive fact that when the relative entropy is large, its rate of decay toward equilibrium is faster.</p>
<p>
<b>Martingale property of the optimal drift.</b> Now for the proof of <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqlogsob">(5)</a>. Let <img alt="{dW_t = dB_t + v_t\,dt} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BdW_t+%3D+dB_t+%2B+v_t%5C%2Cdt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dW_t = dB_t + v_t\,dt} "/> be the entropy-optimal process with <img alt="{W_1 \sim f \,d\gamma_n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_1+%5Csim+f+%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_1 \sim f \,d\gamma_n} "/>. We need one more fact about <img alt="{\{v_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Bv_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{v_t\}} "/>: The optimal drift is a martingale, i.e. <img alt="{\mathop{\mathbb E}[v_t \mid v_s] = v_s} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Bv_t+%5Cmid+v_s%5D+%3D+v_s%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathop{\mathbb E}[v_t \mid v_s] = v_s} "/> for <img alt="{s &lt; t} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs+%3C+t%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{s &lt; t} "/>.</p>
<p>
Let’s give two arguments to support this.</p>
<p>
<b>Argument one: Brownian bridges.</b> First, note that by the chain rule for relative entropy, we have: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}) = D(W_1 \,\|\, B_1) + \int D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]} \mid W_1=B_1=x) f(x) d\gamma_n(x)\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%29+%3D+D%28W_1+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_1%29+%2B+%5Cint+D%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C%5C%2C+B_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5Cmid+W_1%3DB_1%3Dx%29+f%28x%29+d%5Cgamma_n%28x%29%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]}) = D(W_1 \,\|\, B_1) + \int D(W_{[0,1]} \,\|\, B_{[0,1]} \mid W_1=B_1=x) f(x) d\gamma_n(x)\,.  "/></p>
<p> But from optimality, we know that the latter expectation is zero. Therefore <img alt="{f \,d\gamma_n} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf+%5C%2Cd%5Cgamma_n%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{f \,d\gamma_n} "/>-almost surely, we have </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  D(W_{[0,1]} \,\| B_{[0,1]} \mid W_1=B_1=x) = 0\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++D%28W_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5C%2C%5C%7C+B_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D+%5Cmid+W_1%3DB_1%3Dx%29+%3D+0%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  D(W_{[0,1]} \,\| B_{[0,1]} \mid W_1=B_1=x) = 0\,.  "/></p>
<p> This implies that if we condition on the endpoint <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/>, then <img alt="{W_{[0,1]}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_%7B%5B0%2C1%5D%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{W_{[0,1]}} "/> is a Brownian bridge (i.e., a Brownian motion conditioned to start at <img alt="{0} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{0} "/> and end at <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/>).</p>
<p>
This implies that <img alt="{\mathop{\mathbb E}[v_t \mid v_s, W_1=x] = v_s} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Bv_t+%5Cmid+v_s%2C+W_1%3Dx%5D+%3D+v_s%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathop{\mathbb E}[v_t \mid v_s, W_1=x] = v_s} "/>, as one can check that a Brownian bridge <img alt="{\{\hat B_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B%5Chat+B_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{\hat B_t\}} "/> with endpoint <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/> is described by the drift process <img alt="{d\hat B_t = dB_t + \frac{x-\hat B_t}{1-t}\,dt} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bd%5Chat+B_t+%3D+dB_t+%2B+%5Cfrac%7Bx-%5Chat+B_t%7D%7B1-t%7D%5C%2Cdt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{d\hat B_t = dB_t + \frac{x-\hat B_t}{1-t}\,dt} "/>, and </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\frac{x-\hat B_t}{1-t} \,\Big|\, B_{[0,s]}\right] = \frac{x-\hat B_s}{1-s}\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Cleft%5B%5Cfrac%7Bx-%5Chat+B_t%7D%7B1-t%7D+%5C%2C%5CBig%7C%5C%2C+B_%7B%5B0%2Cs%5D%7D%5Cright%5D+%3D+%5Cfrac%7Bx-%5Chat+B_s%7D%7B1-s%7D%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \mathop{\mathbb E}\left[\frac{x-\hat B_t}{1-t} \,\Big|\, B_{[0,s]}\right] = \frac{x-\hat B_s}{1-s}\,.  "/></p>
<p>
That seemed complicated. There is a simpler way to see this: Given <img alt="{\hat B_s} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+B_s%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\hat B_s} "/> and any bridge <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> from <img alt="{\hat B_s} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Chat+B_s%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\hat B_s} "/> to <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/>, every “permutation” of the infinitesimal steps in <img alt="{\gamma} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cgamma%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\gamma} "/> has the same law (by commutativity, they all land at <img alt="{x} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{x} "/>). Thus the marginal law of <img alt="{dB_t + v_t\,dt} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BdB_t+%2B+v_t%5C%2Cdt%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{dB_t + v_t\,dt} "/> at every point <img alt="{t \geq s} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bt+%5Cgeq+s%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{t \geq s} "/> should be the same. In particular, </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \mathop{\mathbb E}[v_t\,dt \mid v_s] = \mathop{\mathbb E}[dB_t + v_t\,dt \mid v_s] = \mathop{\mathbb E}[dB_s + v_s \,ds \mid v_s] = v_s\,ds\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5Bv_t%5C%2Cdt+%5Cmid+v_s%5D+%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5BdB_t+%2B+v_t%5C%2Cdt+%5Cmid+v_s%5D+%3D+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5BdB_s+%2B+v_s+%5C%2Cds+%5Cmid+v_s%5D+%3D+v_s%5C%2Cds%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \mathop{\mathbb E}[v_t\,dt \mid v_s] = \mathop{\mathbb E}[dB_t + v_t\,dt \mid v_s] = \mathop{\mathbb E}[dB_s + v_s \,ds \mid v_s] = v_s\,ds\,.  "/></p>
<p>
<b>Argument two: Change of measure.</b> There is a more succinct (though perhaps more opaque) way to see that <img alt="{\{v_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Bv_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{v_t\}} "/> is a martingale. Note that the process <img alt="{\nabla P_{1-t} f(B_t) = P_{1-t} \nabla f(B_t)} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cnabla+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28B_t%29+%3D+P_%7B1-t%7D+%5Cnabla+f%28B_t%29%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\nabla P_{1-t} f(B_t) = P_{1-t} \nabla f(B_t)} "/> is a Doob martingale. But we have <img alt="{v_t = \frac{\nabla P_{1-t} f(W_t)}{P_{1-t} f(W_t)}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bv_t+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B%5Cnabla+P_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29%7D%7BP_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{v_t = \frac{\nabla P_{1-t} f(W_t)}{P_{1-t} f(W_t)}} "/> and we also know that <img alt="{\frac{1}{P_{1-t} f(W_t)} = \frac{1}{M_t}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BP_%7B1-t%7D+f%28W_t%29%7D+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BM_t%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\frac{1}{P_{1-t} f(W_t)} = \frac{1}{M_t}} "/> is precisely the change of measure that makes <img alt="{\{W_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_t\}} "/> into Brownian motion.</p>
<p>
<b>Proof of the log-Sobolev inequality.</b> In any case, now we are ready for the proof of <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#eqlogsob">(5)</a>. It also comes straight from <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1006.3028">Lehec’s paper</a>. Since <img alt="{\{v_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7Bv_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{v_t\}} "/> is a martingale, we have <img alt="{\mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2 \leq \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_1\|^2} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cv_t%5C%7C%5E2+%5Cleq+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cv_1%5C%7C%5E2%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2 \leq \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_1\|^2} "/>. So by Theorem <a href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/#thmfollmer">1</a>: </p>
<p align="center"><img alt="\displaystyle  \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(f) = \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2\,dt \leq \frac12 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_1\|^2 = \frac12 \mathop{\mathbb E}\, \frac{\|\nabla f(W_1)\|^2}{f(W_1)^2} = \frac12 \mathop{\mathbb E}\, \frac{\|\nabla f(B_1)\|^2}{f(B_1)}\,.  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle++%5Cmathrm%7BEnt%7D_%7B%5Cgamma_n%7D%28f%29+%3D+%5Cfrac12+%5Cint_0%5E1+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cv_t%5C%7C%5E2%5C%2Cdt+%5Cleq+%5Cfrac12+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C%5C%7Cv_1%5C%7C%5E2+%3D+%5Cfrac12+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C+%5Cfrac%7B%5C%7C%5Cnabla+f%28W_1%29%5C%7C%5E2%7D%7Bf%28W_1%29%5E2%7D+%3D+%5Cfrac12+%5Cmathop%7B%5Cmathbb+E%7D%5C%2C+%5Cfrac%7B%5C%7C%5Cnabla+f%28B_1%29%5C%7C%5E2%7D%7Bf%28B_1%29%7D%5C%2C.++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\displaystyle  \mathrm{Ent}_{\gamma_n}(f) = \frac12 \int_0^1 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_t\|^2\,dt \leq \frac12 \mathop{\mathbb E}\,\|v_1\|^2 = \frac12 \mathop{\mathbb E}\, \frac{\|\nabla f(W_1)\|^2}{f(W_1)^2} = \frac12 \mathop{\mathbb E}\, \frac{\|\nabla f(B_1)\|^2}{f(B_1)}\,.  "/></p>
<p>The latter quantity is <img alt="\frac12 I(f)  " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cfrac12+I%28f%29++&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="\frac12 I(f)  "/>.  In the last equality, we used the fact that <img alt="{\frac{1}{f(W_1)}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bf%28W_1%29%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\frac{1}{f(W_1)}} "/> is precisely the change of measure that turns <img alt="{\{W_t\}} " class="latex" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7BW_t%5C%7D%7D+&amp;bg=FFFFFF&amp;fg=000000&amp;s=0" title="{\{W_t\}} "/> into Brownian motion. </p></div></content><updated planet:format="November 21, 2015 07:07 PM">2015-11-21T19:07:36Z</updated><published planet:format="November 21, 2015 07:07 PM">2015-11-21T19:07:36Z</published><category term="Expository"/><category term="Math"/><category term="Brownian motion"/><category term="Follmer drift"/><category term="Gaussian space"/><category term="Ito's lemma"/><category term="Log-Sobolev inequality"/><category term="stochastic calculus"/><author><name>James</name></author><source><id>https://tcsmath.wordpress.com</id><logo>https://s0.wp.com/i/buttonw-com.png</logo><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml"/><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/osd.xml" rel="search" type="application/opensearchdescription+xml"/><link href="https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/?pushpress=hub" rel="hub" type="text/html"/><subtitle>some mathematics &amp; computation</subtitle><title>tcs math</title><updated planet:format="December 17, 2018 05:29 AM">2018-12-17T05:29:01Z</updated><planet:module>toc</planet:module><planet:format>atom10</planet:format><planet:http_last_modified>Fri, 13 Apr 2018 03:53:48 GMT</planet:http_last_modified><planet:bozo>false</planet:bozo><planet:items_per_page>40</planet:items_per_page><planet:css-id>tcs-math</planet:css-id><planet:face>jrl.jpeg</planet:face><planet:name>tcs math</planet:name><planet:http_location>https://tcsmath.wordpress.com/feed/</planet:http_location><planet:http_status>301</planet:http_status></source></entry>
